message:
HOW-TO TUESDAY: Model-worthy brows!

Embrace your inner model (like this gorgeous babe!) with super-bold feature brows! Groom them by brushing your brows upward, and use small scissors to trim the ends of any long, stray hairs. Next, stand in front of a mirror and find the highest point of your brow, then tweeze directly below this point that you have located. Less is more, so go easy! Try not to remove more than two rows of hair, as thickness is key. 

Next, draw short soft lines with our Eyebrow Pencil to fill in your brows. Smudge the colour with clean fingertips to make the look softer (but keep within the lines!). Finish off with a thin layer of our clear Extender lash & Brow Mascara to keep everything neat.
comments: Too many people get this horribly wrong... i think brows look stupid and hairy when brushed up like that! I've had thick eyebrows my entire life.. I hate them, no way I'd make them stand out more.. yuck!!! cool :)

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Two-tone lips!

This look is ALL about vibrant, bold lip colours so make sure your lips are smooth and flake-free first! Apply your fave Australis liquid foundation to clean dry lips with your fingers, creating a flat canvas for the colour. Allow to dry for a few minutes, then blot with a clean tissue to remove excess oil. 

Pick two contrasting shades of our Colour Inject Mineral Lipstick, and apply them carefully to either your top or bottom lip. Use a lip brush to get your edges SUPER neat, blot and reapply! Lightly dust your lips with our Ready Set Finishing Powder to make this look last for HOURS!

P.S. This cute model is from We Are Handsome's MBFW show earlier this year! What a babe!

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Super easy stained lips!

We love this look - lipstick with a romantic twist! Apply moisturising lip balm to your kisser and let it soak in. After a couple of minutes, clean it off with a dry tissue to remove any flakiness and get your lips really smooth! Run a warm, clean fingertip over your lipstick and then dab it onto your lips. Concentrate the colour on the centre of your lips and blend it outwards. Try this with our Colour Inject Mineral Lipstick in 'Salsa' or 'Boogie Woogie'!

message: Click 'like' if you ALWAYS wear Primer! xx
comments:
prefer BB cream! Love the gold  M.A.C Primer is a Must .. How do u apply primer? dont use paint bad for your health What primer used for  It's my MUST HAVE!!!!! eye, face and lip primers, for me it's just as important as a moisturiser! Those waiting a flawless full coverage do the following:

* in the morning remove excess sweat and oil with a makeup wipe (i cleanse tone and exfoliate the night before when i remove my makeup) 
* apply a day cream with sunscreen all over the face and neck
*let it dry for a minute and then apply australis primer with fingers all over face and neck
* apply australis mineral liquid foundation first with a brush then apply extra on parts that need a bit more coverage with fingers. blend edges with fingers 
*apply australis fresh and flawless with a hard sponge or flat kubuki and make sure you actually press it firm into skin
* apply a gentle sweep of australis ready set go finishing powder with a large kubuki all over.

rough prices:
makeup wipes: $4
moisturiser with sunscreen: $10
australis primer: $12
australis liquid foundation: $20
australis fresh and flawless pressed power: $12
ready set go finishing powder $15

TOTAL:$73 
bare in mind those products will last on average 3 months. so only $24 a month.....less than a dollar a day for beautiful makeup. 
you could easily add a shadow pallet and mascara and keep it under $100.

honestly I've spent $70 on a single makeup product before and unless you are trying to impress someone with a brand name then go for Australis. its cheap but the products are so good and easy to use.

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Making your eyes pop!

Make your eyes really stand out with some clever shading ;) Using our 'Totally Busted' Paparazzi Perfect HD Eyeshadow compact, apply a wash of the sand eyeshadow with your fingers from your lash line up to your crease. Then smudge the white shadow from the same compact from your crease up to your eye brows - concentrating it on your brow bone. Use a soft fluffy brush and blend and smooth any harsh edges. Then apply the white shadow to the inner half of your lower lash line. Follow up with your fave eyeliner for a simple eye look that will accentuate your peepers xx

message: Beauty tip! Don't do your make-up on one whole side of your face before doing the other side... Try doing each step for both sides if you need help getting things even. Apply your eyeshadow to both your peepers, then eyeliner for both eyes, then finally mascara! xx

LOL! who would do that??? :S Does anybody do that?? If so, weird......  That's actually how I do my makeup. I do each step separately. Foundation, powder, blush, mascara, creme eyeliner, liquid eyeliner, eyeshadow. On both sides on my face. I honestly don't know someone who would do it one side at a time. i thought everyone did their make-up step by step?? lol I've never done one side then the other...ever XD I mean, it'd be weird....and my brushes would get all mixy-coloured :S No shit? Lol We have heard of some ladies who do both eyeshadow and eyeliner on one eye before moving on to the other side. Whatever works, but we think it helps to do just one side if you can't get it even :)

HOW TO TUESDAY: Prepping your eye area!

Get your peepers ready for gorgeous eye make-up looks with your two new best friends: Eyeshadow Primer & Concealer!

Using a concealer brush, apply the purple concealer from our 4-in-1 Conceal Correct palette to any dark under-eye circles. Less is more, so build up the colour ever-so-slightly! Once that is dry, apply the skin-coloured concealer over the purple concealer with a clean brush. Use your fingers to warm the concealer to make it seem more natural. Don't forget to blend the concealer in! Next, apply a thin layer of our Eyeshadow Primer to your eyelids, from your lash line to your brow bone. If you're planning on glamming it up and applying eyeshadow to your lower lash line, dab a little Primer there too!

All primed, prepped and ready for your fave eye make-up look, like this one! ;)

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Keep your brushes beautiful!

We <3 make-up brushes because they give you flawless and gorgeous look... But only if you keep them in prime condition! 

Moisten your brush with warm water first, then lather up gentle face wash or baby shampoo on the back of your hand and swirl the bristles through it. Rinse well until the water runs clear. Blot off excess water with a clean tissue and gently reshape the bristles with your fingers.

Hot tip: never handle the bristles too roughly or try to pull them apart!
comments: At the college (makeup artistry) we learnt to use a mild antibacterial wash (I use lavender dettol as it smells great even after brushes have dried) to clean the brushes daily..same technique as above, just with the added benefit of an antibacterial agent to thoroughly cleanse between clients. Also a good brush cleaner or alcohol spray is great for when you don't have time to wash and dry brushes during the day. Good tip, Zoe! Thanks xx You can also use isopropyl alcohol in a spray bottle... spray the brush and dry with a paper towel. If you like to shampoo your brushes don't use really hot water because you might melt the glue and cause the brush to fall apart. Omg thank you Great advice, Gemma! Thanks for sharing <3 <3 Just tried this and oh my God  they look bran new yay

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Pastel French mani!

Get the season's hottest look on your nails with Australis! Apply a thin layer of our Top & Base coat to shaped and buffed nails. Once dry, apply two coats of our creamy Peek-A-Boo Nail Colour. Make sure it's super dry, then use French manicure strips across your nails, leaving a gap of a few millimetres before the tip. message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: Straight up liner

This is one for girls who LOVE winged eyeliner but can't get their lines straight ;) On clean eyes, use two pieces of magic tape to create a triangle in the outer corner of your eyes. Using our Liquid Liner, fill in shape created by the tape, wait 30 seconds for it to dry, then remove the tape slowly.

Fill in any gaps and fix up any wonky edges if needed, then line your upper lash line. Follow up with lashing of our Killer Curves Mascara. Practice this at home a few times to get each eye super-even!

P.S. If you have steady hands and can freehand this... Go for it! ;)
comments: Where do I find this magic tape or will Hollywood tape do pretty much the same thing?? Hi Michelle! Hollywood tape is actually more like double sided tape, so might not work as well :P Most news agencies and supermarkets will stock magic tape. xx Thanks for that Australis. I will be investing in some :-)

message:
HOW TO TUESDAY: A super-sultry, smokey eye with a twist!

This season's hottest smokey eye look sees gorgeous brown hues taking centre stage! Prep eyes with our Eyeshadow Primer, then apply the medium brown shade of our Paparazzi Perfect HD Eye Shadow in 'Snap Attack' all over your lids with clean fingers. Use a sponge applicator and apply a light wash of the same eyeshadow under your lower lashes. Use clean fingers and apply the darkest brown from the same palette lightly over your mobile lids, then 'pat' on the eyeshadow to add to the intensity and build up the colour. Use a smaller eyeshadow brush or a clean cotton bud to add the darker shade to your lower lash line.

Line your upper and lower lash line with our 'Midnight' Stayput Liner, and don't forget to give your waterline some lovin' too. Follow up with lashings of mascara and use a fan brush to flick away any eyeshadow fallout under your eyes.

Don't stress if you're a bit on the messy side... This look isn't about being ladylike, it's about being edgy!

message:
Thanks to Shaaanxo for listing our 10Hr Wear Eye Pencil as one of her fave products of the month! What's your Australis must-have product?

P.S. Skip to 5.44 for the best part ;)

HOW TO TUESDAY: Get your glow on this Summer!

We can't wait for the weather to heat up, so here's our Summery tutorial for the week!

Apply our Paparazzi Perfect Tinted Moisturiser over fresh, clean skin. Use your fingers to blend to give you a smooth base. Pump out your chosen High Lights Mineral High Lighter (Gold for darker or warmer skin tones, Pearl for cooler or lighter skin) on the back of your hand, and use your fingertips to lightly dot them along your cheekbones and the bridge of your nose. Blend the dots into your skin in circular motions so there are no harsh lines. If you tend to be a victim of shiny skin, lightly dust our Ready Set Go Finishing Powder over the top and set it with our Finishing Spritz... Bring on Summer!
Hit 'SHARE' if you agree. Times a million ;)

message: Click like if you SMILE when you apply blush to find the apples of your cheeks!!!
comments:
NOOOOO you shouldnt do that!! when you stop smiling the apples of your cheeks drop which "pulls" your face down making you look older! Exactly!! ^^ kimberley knows whats up!
the "in" look for blush is to apply it in a soft blended circle on your cheekbones - looks natural but also "lifts" the face! @kimberly tht only applies to older people, makes no difference with people who still have the 'elasticity" i their skin lol if u apply from out to in like ear to cheek it fine but i generlly pull the "fish/duck face" to find my hollows and above that while pulling the face i aply blush, it goes on well and the effect slims down the face, inseD OF SMILING AND BLENDNG which places it in a bigger spce Loving all the tips, ladies! Keep them coming ;) if you dont believe me,put the tips of your fingers on the apples of your cheeks while smiling,then stop smiling,they drop thats why i ASO suck in cheeks when finding cheekbones and above that is the cheek...so as cheeks are sucked in i apply blush, it applies it to a slimmer amounnt o faace lol i smile to blend out and i done that what u saidand no dierence lol

having foundation issues at the moe :/ Haha too many! I even have two in this picture. Love the paparazzi effect one!! I have two, one with fuller coverage than the other. I alternate between the two, depending on the condition of my skin. 8! For when I tan, when I'm paler, fuller coverage and I like to mix some to get my perfect concoction! 0 :( I don't really have any. I can never find any that match my skin tone Absolutely none..! one for everyday and one full coverage i currently have one and usually i only have one at a time I have a Mineral Powder, Panstick, 2 BB creams, Pressed Powder and 3 other medium coverage Foundations in different shades. I reckon I'm all set! I have several - for day/night, different occasions, different covrrage, rtc I have a few foundations, but im really loving BB creams at the moment I have one and its this brand.. great coverage two i mix them together cause it matches my skin tone better the any of the others would on their own (if that makes sense) I usually stick to the same one as I know it works and what I want it to look like. If you ever stop making your pressed powder in the square case ill be ruined. Such a staple! Paparazzi perfect foundation is pretty great too. I have none! So glad I'm not the only person with eight different kinds...Paparazzi HD is my favourite Australis one. About 4 :s I struggle with matching my skin colour! I have tonnes of old ones but now I've found the right one I have 8 liquid types and a handful of presses/loose powders :) I'm still trying to find the right one that stays Just the one. message: Every girl has her own make-up secrets... What's your top tip for getting your foundation perfect? Comment and share! xx
comments:
Primer!!! Good quality facial moisturiser with spf cannot go past!!! I always moisturise then use a bb cream and let it"Set" so to speak. Then I use a damp beauty blender sponge and use the bottom of it to dab/stipple my foundation on.I use a finger for my concealer and finish with a fine layer of pressed powder,then I do highlight/contour/blush. I find australis foundation work best for my skin,dont know why they just do. My fav is the one with the brush(cant remember the name)stayput(my current and a past fav) and PPHD foundation Primer and a good foundation brush :) A good buffing or stippling brush makes a big difference Taking the time to find the right one for your skin. And a good skin care routine so you have the best base you can. Skin specific primer, apply foundation with a brush, depending on the look im going for I select the brush and technique accordingly, buff if required, press foundation into skin with fingers so it looks more like skin and then place and buff powder to set. Spritz with finishing spray for all day wear and added hydration, sometimes I carry a purse pack to give my makeup a pick me up during the day :-) Primer and a really good brush. starting off with a clean base is a must for me. Your foundation can only do so much. Whats important is that your skin is clean, fresh, moisturised and primed before you even go near the concealers and foundations. I also like adding a little bit of highlighter on the highest part of my cheekbones and contouring with gel bronzer before i pop on my liquid foundation. This means i can have subtle definition to my features without going too OTT with contouring. Lastly, Australis finishing spritz and a light dusting of the ready set go powder finishes the look. Always apply it to clean, moisturised and primed skin for a smooth base. Use more than one type of foundation at a time. Different areas of the face may need different coverage (Skin is rarely the same all over) I use my stippling brush to blend it out! Cleanse & moisturise daily if not twice a day.. Primer, foundation- I tend to dampen my foundation brush just a tad it seems to do a better job(for me anyway) and def use pressed powder to set:)  Hydrate skin well 
Set make up with powder I exfoliate my skin first as I don't often wear foundation to give it a smooth base. And follow up with a moisturizer. Primer then i'll stipple on the foundation, using my clean hands after to smooth it all out and blend it into the skin to make it look more natural. Follow up with setting powder and i'm good to go! i go outside in the morning to see what the weather is doing. after sussing it all out, i apply my foundation outside on my verandah making sure i don't cake it on and so i match the daylight :) i do my skincare first and then apply my makeup I use the Australia's finishing spray as a primer when I'm out of primer and after I've finished my make up. Double duty! cleanse prime apply and blot using your Fresh and Flawless Pressed Powder! My all time fave product :) Amazing tips here, ladies! xx

message:
Did you know that one of our best-selling foundations is our Fresh & Flawless Pressed Powder? The 2-in-1 foundation and pressed powder is perfect if you have senstitive, oily or problem-prone skin... Plus the built in compact mirror is our fave!!!

Buy it online here: http://www.australiscosmetics.com.au/product/46010/f~f-pressed-powder
comments: I will be using this product for as long as I live! I only discovered this a few months ago but nothing compares to it. I use it to set my foundation and it just gives me a bit of added coverage. Absolutely love it Favourite foundation I've tried! The best :) Will be buying this next week. I've been looking for this product for ages! BEST POWDER IN THE UNIVERSE! I have even got my friends hooked on this! And to me it's like the mac studio fix powder. But cheaper and better! And I have nearly run out waaaah :'( I love most Australis products, but found with this one the shades didn't go light enough :/ Why arent there any shaded for darker people? Lots of dark skinned people live in Australia. Aboriginals, people of african/indian/middle eastern descent and other similarly dark skinned people. OMG your pressed powder is the BEST!!! I use this everyday. Best coverage Love it :) It's been my #1 product for years! I adore it, never stop making it! xx The darkest shade of liquid foundation is 'golden tan' - this goes perfectly with my skin tone. However, the darkest shade of the pressed powder is far whiter than the golden tan. I find this incredibly problematic - if I put on that pressed powder, it looks like I'm trying to give myself a lighter skin tone (which I'm not, I'm just trying to even out  my skin). I find it really annoying that with the pressed powder range, Australis isn't catering to the section of the population who happen to be darker-skinned than the powder. Is there anything in the works to rectify this? I certainly hope so. All your makeup thus far has been amazing... but please don't overlook those of us who just weren't fortunate enough to be born white. i never use anything else, and i recommend it to everyone. NEVER stop making it please!!! :) Thanks so much for your feedback girls! Glad to hear you are loving our foundations. We will pass your feedback onto the rest of the team for future developments x I was told by XoFemmeBeauty, best purchase I ever made :)

message: Foundation tip! Try to wash your foundation brush as often as you can. Clean brushes = happy skin! Plus have you ever tried to apply foundation with a cakey, dried up brush?! Not fun ;)
comments: After every use like a nerd I keep telling my sister this Laura LaLa Hartman Ill learn one day :) i never really wash my brushes i find it takes wayyyy too long to dry.  instead i use makeup wipes to get all the colour and gunk out of the brush.  quick, easy and very effective and ive had my brushes for ages and they are still in great condition!! I tried to wash my australis mineral powder brush with shampoo and when it dried it was yukky... how/what is the besy way to clean them? I use a sponge I use brush cleaner after every use. You can get wet and 'dry' brush cleaners great for sink or tissue use. Bacteria doesnt always give off a high hum factor...re using a foundation brush is just like turning your undies inside out and wearing them again :/ Baby shampoo works too. Hey there, Kirsty! We'd recommend making sure that you make sure you remove all traces of the foundation with the shampoo and then check that you're also rinsed out all traces of the shampoo. Reshape the brush and let it dry :) If that doesn't work, some companies also sell brush cleaner that are specially designed to do the trick! Baby shampoo works for me, gets everything out and doesnt hurt the brushes :) I wash after pretty much every use before my foundations seem to make it go weird anyway

message: Online shopping vs. shopping at a mall... Which do you love more?
comments: both online for the bargains, shops to try on/test products (: Shopping at mall shops/mall Shoping at mall I prefer online shopping because I tend to be frowned upon at beauty counters because of my looks. Both but usually in store because you don't have to pay postage/shipping and you can test out the product. Online! The deals are better, the prices are usually cheaper (if purchasing from overseas like I do) and it feels like your birthday when your parcel arrives definitely mall - can swatch and test all the colours & textures rather than just guessing what it will look like Online On line! Australian retailers need to wake up and realize we can not afford their 300% mark up rate for products. Sad state of affairs when you can buy online oversea's and get it posted to you cheaper then you can go to shop and buy!

message: Beauty question time! Which do you prefer to apply first: foundation or concealer? #theimportantquestions
comments:
concealer 1st It really depends what i want to cover up. 
But usually, i do foundation first. Foundation and then concealer. But concealer under foundation for extra coverage on blemishes. Foundation first :) Primer then foundation then concelor under the eyes Foundation definitely :) have to brighten those damn circles under eyes haha Foundation first, then I can see if I need to apply concealer :) foundation foundation. sometimes thats enough to fix any imperfections. Foundation first then concealer foundation then concealer 
your not going to conceal much if you put foundation over the top Concealer first then apply foundation Foundation This has changed my life. I thought there was only one way to do it. Primer then put foundation n then see where concealer is needed :)) Foundation, concealer then set with powder. primer, foundation, concealer then setting powder. i have that foundation haha Foundation, then you know what areas need concealed and avoid caking on too much product. Foundation then concealer foundation then concealer. foundation! way i was taught in beauty college Primer, concealer then foundation. Cause my concealer is the green one? Foundation foundation, concealer then ready set go finishing powder and I am off lol Primer, colour correction, foundation, concealer, setting powder :) Primer, Foundation then concealer  Foundation Primer foundation just in case I don't need concealer! Foundation unless Its powder foundation foundation then concealer Foundation, councler and then powder foundation on top! Foundation first I agree, foundation then concealer. :) Bb cream foundation then i use concealer to highlight under the eyes then set with a trans powder = a flawless coverage and keep my face moisterised with bb to prevent drying or breakouts on the skin :) Im a yellow undertine plz do in tht shade range in this foundation i love it but can't use it due to the color shade plz plz do it in like loreal w1 shade or like palest pale yellow undertone like estee lauder double wear in shade bone Concealer.... Concealer Foundation, if you apply concealer on top of your foundation you get a lot more coverage & it blends out easier :) Concealer. If its a green/purple/salmon concealer than I'll apply that first. If its a beige concealer I'll apply it afterwards I thought you had to do concealer first because when blending you would rub off the foundation if it was already on.  I see now most do it the other way. I do a bit of each depends how I feel at the time Foundation Concealer to hide certain things. Bags under eyes. Scars etc Foundation Concealer then foundation. Works for me! Do a "Zorro" mask over the eyes of concealer, then apply foundation everywhere and touch up with concealer at the end. Works a treat for dark circles. Foundation ;) foundation first and concealer next. You will ruin the texture if you put concealer on first

Im so lazy at taking my makeup off at night, I give the mailman heart failure every time I greet him at the door!! I'd create a face spray. You just spray it on and it knows what colours to put where, it does your eyes, lips and cheeks. A flawless foundation that had your skin looking like a photo out of Vogue magazine!!! Not a line or blemish in sight! :) A foundation that knew where to become highlighted and where to be darker due to pigmentation of your skin , that just seeped into your skin to be perfect for you , but while it's doing that , it's healing any blemish and not clogging your pores , comes out with a special make up remover designed specifically for it A mascara wand that has two settings- one to apply mascara (any colour) and another setting to  remove the mascara by simply brushing your lashes :) saves the pain of eye makeup remover in your eyes everynight!  Lipstick changes to your mood but its never a dull colour because then youd be able to have funky colours on your lips all the time A makeup brand called allyd and i would create instant makeup removers  perfect winging eyeliner yummy smelling lipstick the works:) A foundation that filled in wrinkles leaving your skin flawless and firm especially under the eyes and forehead! A make up setting spray that highlighted your areas where lit hit, defined your cheekbones, got rid of any pimples or wrinkles and just made you look flawless! a nude lipstick that wasn't drying and didn't settle into lines! I am yet to find one of those! A machine that does all your makeup for you speedy including gluing on eyelashes I get harassed at how long I take :( I would create a product that blurs and covers imperfections,long lasting,easy to remove,good for the skin that comes in an applicator that releases only what you need and applies it for you. it would be a primer,concealer,foundation and powder all in one probably impossible but some thing thats like a mask that you put on your face and it does all your make up in seconds for the times you're in a rush or lazy haha Makeup removing wipes that take makeup off in one go. Would be good if it could do the nail polish at the same time. For those times where I'm too drunk or too lazy at night and do a half a*s job and wake up with makeup all over my pillow. Mascara that can be different colours!! :) Two in one mascara and eyeliner I would create a spray that would instantly take your makeup off, you just spray it on your face & it will come off, much easier than washing your face every time you wear it :) Def a good makeup remover hard to find one and something to make eyeliner easier to apply i wold create a foundation that covered every imperfection like pores and freckles and red marks and pimples while still being good for your skin and fighting acne while you war it A lip pallette with clear matte mixes and satin mixes so you can mix your own unique  colours also with lipsticks you already have. And it would be budge proof. A nail polish that will never chip unless you use nail polish remover and the nail polish will quickly come off I would create a big makeup palate with simple neutral everyday colours like one blush a couple of eyeshadows a bronzer and it had an eyeliner , mascara and concealer you you pull out and use to create your everyday look with one palette <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+0089>haha I don't know if this makes sense but it does to me I would also create a nail polish that changes colour depending on your mood so like a mood ring but on your nails so that if you are angry or sad or upset people could tell and try help and Also it Dosent chip Is there such thing as a waterproof eyebrow pencil?? I need one! One workout at the gym and sweat city sees my eye brow colour drip down my face!! A dream mascara that gives me beautiful full and long lashes and has lash conditioning properties.  It will also last the day without flaking off or smudging  And will be easy to remove without damaging my natural lashes. :-) A full-face premade look you could press on eye makeup that only too 1 wipe across your lid to have perfect multi coloured eye make upon i would create a huge makeup palate with half been neutral colours and the other half been pinks and purples of all sort of different shades, cos those are my favs go to everyday colors i would also want to create the perfect brushes and make them an affordable price A gel face mask which is actually the color of your normal foundation and comes in matte or moisturising with holes in it that you fill yourself with blush, bronzer and eye shadows. So you always have the perfect contour area, blush area and eyeshadow areas. Like painting within the lines <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+009C> I would create an eyeliner that makes the perfect wing everytime you apply it! A foundation that prevents an oily ness showing until you remove it. Every foundation I've tried that is good for oily skin always ends up showing a bit of oil by the end of the day a foundation that would match your skin tone once it set so you wouldnt get makeup lines Eyeliner that does not smudge up the top in the creases of your eyes but would wash away easily. An eyeliner that automatically creates symmetrical wings so you dont have to spend hours evening them up every morning! The perfect contour cream that blends into your foundation, almost like a cream bronzer with minimal shimmer. My perfect product! a foundation that made your skin flawless, and you didn't have to take it off and it didn't rub off so your skin always looked that perfect ;) An airbrush foundation that works just like photoshop! I would make a foundation that had a coating so i could touch/rub my face and it would rub off on my hands or clothing ! :) Matt finish CC Cream with SPF30 A lipstick you apply that has the effect of ombrï¿½ lips and changes colour with your mood . make up that lasts forever, one application and set for life haha Make up that no teachers can see just you and people around you so you can wear as much make up as you want at school matte bronzer in a variety of shades and undertones..its hard work finding the perfect one! Waterproof natural white eyeliner because natural = good and white eyeliner never stays on long enough I would totally create something to make my 27year old face with lines look 18years old with no lines!!!! Eyebrow Falsies! Saves having to groom and define every morning, not everyone is blessed with thick eyebrows I think you guys have it covered but id love to  create a perfect matte shadow palette xx Something that even I can't sweat off! I hardly wear makeup because I sweat way too much :( All day Long lasting foundation.....as mine never seems to stay on all day ombre lipstick <3 A brush with blusher colour and contour bronzer colour on each half, so you could blush and contour/bronze at the same time. Also maybe detachable brush heads for different colours of blush and bronzer! Two in one mascara and eyeliner Mascara and eyeliner in one! Smokey eyes and a bright red lip Lipstick that lasts perfectly untill you wash it off. Makeup that won't budge unless you want it to -.- A matte liquid eyeliner pen that won't budge Liquid Eyeliner that went on perfectly everytime! Well we our all beautiful people so we dont even need make up :D but if I could I would make a lipstick on one end a shimmer gloss on the other end xxx I'd create a GENUINE oil eliminating foundation :) A foundation which made your skin look perfect without making your u look caked... The perfect colour i would create a sealant for around my lips so no lipstick would smudge off it and also would have the perfect shape! Brush-on synthetic Eyelashes in a single mascara wand tube Lipstick that changes colour depending on the lighting - so in natural light your lipstick would adjust to a tone that is flattering in that light, in artificial light it may become a little darker and richer, and in night-time artificial light (like in a club or restaurant) it would adjust to a dark night-time colour.  This would mean you only need to carry one lipstick around for day to night and different environments! A mineral powder with a build-able coverage ! I love wearing mineral powder but sometimes it just doesn't do the trick would be amazing to get one powder that let's you have a light/medium/full coverage ! :)) An instant fine line eraser or a self blending foundation! An instant whole face makeup gun, like Homer Simpson made for Marge but that works a LOT better haha A nail polish that never chips, goes on perfectly, doesn't need base or top coat, only takes one coat, dries instantly, can magically change colour to what I want as often as I want and makes my nails grow! :) Something that makes your skin healthier when you wear it. A foundation, concealer, bronzer and highlighter all in one I would love to create a blush that when applied dry was one colour and when applied wet was another! Choices are great when you get sick of the same look every day :-) A concealer that makes your acne disappear straight away! A lippy that perfectly places itself into the shape of your lips giving you a sharp defined pout that stays all day :) Lipstick which changes with your moods like a mood ring for your lips, you are feeling sexy, it's be red, flirty: hot pink, shy: soft pink etc An eyeshadow that didn't sink in to the lines of my eyes and make my wrinkles more obvious and also that didn't come off when I rub my eyes!

message:
The weather is getting cold but that doesn't mean you can't look HOT! That's why we're giving you the chance to WIN 1 of 5 awesome makeup makeover packs featuring our NEW Full On Foundation! Simply LIKE this image and comment below telling us how you change your beauty routine for winter to enter. Don't forget to share the love with your friends! Good luck babes!

Ends 19/06/2014. Full T&Cs: http://on.fb.me/TImKG7
comments:
I use a thicker lip balm and switch out my lipsticks to plum toned shades! The biggest change is really in skincare routine. Less is more, nice cool tones to suit the weather, but never making it look like it's painted on. I change my beauty routine by adding in more skincare and using different colour lipsticks and shadows Darker and more dramatic eyes,
With plenty of lip balm Extra hydration ï¿½ be it a heavier night time moisturizer, a hydrating serum, and having extra water. Lip balm becomes essential, I also stick to a nude palette for my face and choose darker nail polish shades :) I apply warm toned blush and lippy, then top it off with a sleek winged eyeliner A slightly paler foundation, and lipstick with more depth and vibrancy - all to cheer the chilly days. I have to moisturize like there is no tomorrow as i find winter dries me out. I also wear brighter colour lipsticks to brighten my day :) Lighter foundation, and more moisturiser! Winter makes your skin pretty dry. I live in FNQ so the weather here does not change drastically but if I am wearing gloomier colours like black and grey cardigans or jackets I like to brighten it up with brighter coloured make up or accessories. Red lippie and matching earrings are a fave. I use a rich moisturiser and heavier foundation because my skin isn't as clear in winter. More primer and moisturizer and illumizer to make my skin glow x I change my foundation from liquid to powder as my skin gets drier and use plenty of moisturiser. Change up to a fuller coverage foundation, bit mor highlight and brightening, change up of blushers and deeper lippies. I change from BB cream to foundation, and switch from lipgloss to lipstick for more intense, matte colour. Lighter foundation. i change my routine by using more moisturizing on my skin, using different colours of eye shadows,and always wear lipstick balm before applying the lipstick to have my lips well protected. My foundation becomes ghostly white because my summer tan fades, I combat that with bronzer and blush to add colour. I also don't have to use as much powder because I won't sweat as much. Bright red lipstick is my fave paired with dark mascara and eyebrows is the perfect winter look in my opinion :) moisturise regularly :) Lots of moisturising products and darker lips! (: x I tend to use a lighter foundation, pop on the grey and black eye shadows and bring out the pink lipsticks! I tend to use a lighter coloured foundation and cooler eyeshadow tones :) I also use a lighter moisturiser and more natural coloured lipstick/ lip balm I use more cream products because my skin is a lot drier and I like a more dewy look in winter. I wear more vibrant colours. I keep it natural but have a bold red lip to keep it classy. More water to keep my skin hydrated ,I stay quite natural over winter a little mascara and lip gloss and moisturizer goes,a long way and can make anyone look a million  dollars  :-D I swap out the Australis Matte powder (which is great with my summer bronzer), for the Australis Fresh and Flawless, which is a little softer looking with my blush. I use a pencil eyeliner instead of my usual liquid, and just do half the top outer eye for a more delicate look. I use more mascara and softer, more natural autumn coloured eye shadows (like the one above) and I wear lots of more natural light pink lipsticks. :) I use a heavier moisturizer and also exfoliate and moisturize my lips a lot more so they don't dry out A more dewy foundation finish over matte and more blue and purple eye shadows over bronze. Lip balm is an absolute must! I love using the combo of BB cream and bronzer in winter too highlight and have a dewy look to brighten up my face, adding a bright lippy to add colour to those wintery gloomy days!! xx There's nothing I love more in Winter than my electric blanket but it dries my skin so I moisturise daily. I play around with different eyeshadow colours and lipsticks since I don't have to worry about my makeup melting off, haha. Also because I tend to stick to darker, more plain clothes when it comes to Winter, so I want my makeup to stand out more. In winter I like to switch out my light moisturizer for something a little heavier. Add an extra coat of mascara and ditch the summer gloss for a rich berry lippy. I apply more moisturiser and I wear darker lips Warmer based eyeshadows and deeper lip colour with bold eyebrows Darker plums and ox blood colours for lips, with natural eyes. Or a sheer dark pink-red with brown and gold smokey eyes during the day, so it's not too intense, and sometimes winged liner. Then load up on mascara and apply a rose gold/white liner to make my eyes appear brighter. Clean simple. Making my eyes pop with a catseye... Natural pink lippy and bronzer dreaming of my summer tan I apply more moisturizer to my skin and always apply my BB cream and dewy foundation to finish. Much more use of lip ecfoliant lip balm, moituriser and primer plus some finishing spray dont want my make up to run in the rain :) I love winter make up can pull out cool blue and purple colours for lips and eyes and i always warm up my cheek colour Always wear brighter nail polish and eye shadow in winter to brighten things up a bit. A softer, smokey cat eye and using an illuminator for a dewy glow! I switch my lipstick to tinted lip balm to make sure they're soft and kissable, and I switch my powder foundation for creams and serums for extra hydration :) Bright pink lippy, smoky eyeliner cat eyes, and bb cream <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0097><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+0083><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0097> During winter I have dull sunlight in my bathroom... often leads to mistakes with blending foundation. Thankfully I can sneakily tuck this tragic makeup mishap behind a scarf! Skip the bronzer and exam Skip the bronzer and wear more blush. Once Winter hits I swap in a luminzing primer, break out the vampy lipsticks and keep my skin uber hydrated and exfoliated. I love winter! replace bronzer with blush. also have my eyes darker. I love shades of pinks and subtle greys to warm me up for winter and leave off the powder used in summer :) Yesterday went to the hairdressers had my eyebrows waxed and a new experience my upper lip waxed a few hairs near my nostriles. I use a mist during the day when not wearing any makeup...scented but still additional moisture for the skin I switch it up by using darker lippies and more moisturier! I use winter as a time to improve my skin - I focus on deeper moisturizing and masks.  In the summer, I often don't want to put anything on my skin as I am just so hot, so winter is my time for skin improvement. I like to switch to a stronger mosituriser in winter and to a bold red lip to brighten the cold winter days I probably moisturise my face and body a lot more in the winter because my skin gets a lot dryer from the cold weather.I use more honey balm mainly before I go to bed so that my lips stay nice and smooth :) Burgundy and deep red lipstick,  with browns for eyeshadow and light contouring! And strong eyebrows I change my makeup into brighter colors like powder puff pink lipgloss and a nice blusher and light colored nail polishes I swap my lip gloss to lip stick to make my lip colour stand out a bit more, i'll swap my skin colour blush to a pale pink just for my own creation of a winter look ( and also to go with my winter clothes), i swap skin colour eye shadow to a pink to match my winter clothes aswell and and swap my normal skin bronzer to a darker colour to make me look more tanned to catch up without much sun. #fingerscrossed <3 The bronzer gets replaced by rosy pink cheeks. There's nothing worse than a fake orange winter tan! MY WINTER MAKE-UP ROUTINE FOR COLD NIGHTS OUT WITH CLOSE FRIENDS!

1. Apply primer and foundation.
2. Apply blush or bronzer to enhance your cheekbones.
3. A Smokey eye always looks best with all outfits.
4. Apply a bright coloured lipstick to bring colour to your face! i change up to my pale foundation (have lost my natural summer glow lol) , and use warmer toned eyeshadows and lipsticks... :) I have to change my foundation colour an powder
I go with more red an nudes colours 
An just browns <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+0080> really want to try out that new full on foundation. I change up my beauty routine by using a darker Color lippie, applying intense moisturizer because my skin gets really dry in the winter and i also use a cream color liner on my waterline to brighten up my eyes :]. I use white eyeliner to outline the bottom of my brow, the inside of my bottom lash line and the inner corner of my eye. Helps me seem more awake when all I want to do is sleep! <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+00B4> I use a richer night moisturiser with a serum underneath as my skin gets drier, also use a lip balm underneath lippy - usually a dark nude lip shade for winter or sometimes a light plum shade and switch to a cream blush. During winter I exfoliate and moisturise alot more than I do in the warmer months. I tend to opt for dark smokey eyes, using pencil rather than a liquid eyeliner and I use a volumising mascara. I use blush and bright red lipstick shades for this look. Sometimes I also blend bright colours into the smokey eye to make things a bit interesting and keep the rest of my face subtle. Make sure you stay hydrated, and moisturize.. Its easy to get dry, cracked skin from the cold air to the heated office or homes.. Taking that extra care now in winter will give me extra glowing skin for summer xx Lots of lip balm and slightly lighter foundation. Add a deep berry lipstick. <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008D><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+008C>

Want to define your eyes without going too heavy on the liner? Use the tightlining technique! Line your upper water line and then use a small angled brush to push product up into your lash line.

Image via Makeup.com

message:
A smokey eye is what Friday night is all about, right NZ babes? LIKE this image and COMMENT below telling us your best tip for creating the perfect smokey eye and you could WIN 1 of 8 prize packs featuring our fave smokey eye products!

NZ res. only. Ends 11/08/2014. Full T&Cs: http://bit.ly/acnzsmokifeyeme
comments: Use good brushes and blend properly. Light inner corner to dark outer corner.  Finish with liquid eyeliner and mascara then bam! :) for those of us with glasses.  Magnifying mirror!  You don't want to try and do that around the piddly little flip down glasses thing! Good Brushes and a good base :) Lots of black but blend blend blend! And if necessary look up YouTube tutorials Blend properly using good brushes and I always do a sparkly white inner corner! Makes the smokey eye pop! Blend blend blend untill its to ur desire then eyeliner for the cats eye and mascara to finish.. :D Super fluffy brushes! with an excellent base of course! Blending and quality brushes will be your best friend! =) Line your eyelids thick with black pencil liner then blend out with a brush until the line isn't harsh and also under the eye on the lower lash line.Blend with your choice of colours,line with black liner,and slap on some rocking mascara and ta da!! Really good brushes but also picking a colour that makes your eye colour stand out.... Looks amazing when done properly!! I start with a base color and then work the darker color from the outer corners inward.. I find a smaller fluffy brush is the best for blending.. Then I incorporate the other colors in the middle, blend again and then pop in a highlight color in the inner corner.. Then pull the eye taught and line away. Remember when working with darker colors to ALWAYS tap off the excess on your brush before applying or you will end up looking like a panda and having to re-do all your make up! Blend properly and go for deeper shades instead of black if you're a beginner!<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008B> I use grey on my eyelid and blend shimmery black on the corners :) and mascara and eyeliner.! Different browns with some black eye liner and a good blending brush. A good base, and good brushes Use primer under all the shadows to make the blending part easier, and make the make up last longer. Use good quality brushes and blend. And go for lots of lashes. blend blend blend. oh and great brushes ! Blend for your life! Also doing eyes before the rest of your face because fall out takes the best of us, despite tissue shield attempts Use matte shades as a base, then put shimmery colours over top for more intense colour eyeshadow primer and really blend in your eyeshadow with a good brush :) use good brushes and darker eye shadow in the corners and blend out well then finish with a eye liner and bold lashes :) Blend blend blend and use light to dark don't go straight into with black and yes please with the kit!!:) A pencil liner below the eye and liquid liner above. Great brushes to blend the eyeshadow and beautiful dark mascara Smokey eyeshadow, blend blend blend! Mascara and eyeliner <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0095> Makeup brushes and blending is key! never have harsh lines, use soft shimmers and less is more :) mascara and then placing glitter on your eyes lashes plus a bit of eye liner I think looks superb ;) Use a pencil liner first and then use a dip liner and finish off with a liquid liner. You need to have lighter shades of nude colours in the center of the eye lid and darker black colours on the outer eyelids. Make sure the blend of transformation is even. Finish off with a mascara and curl your eyelashes Blend like there's no tomorrow! I find a dark Grey eyeshadow with a kohl eye line makes for the perfect smokey look  Lots of blending with brushes and adding eye liner for definition <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008A> Blending and smudging but be careful! Start with the lightest colour and blend outwards/darker colours :) also a cat eye is a must for me. Start with a good eye primee Choosing a colour that make your eyes pop is key Be sure to use a Smokey grey eyeliner and dark brown eye shadow with pearlessence Blending n good brushes. And deep shades Apply sticky tape to help have sharp lines + it wont look as messy :) to get a vry good smokey eye, is to NOT start with a black shadow as it will be hard for you to lend it well with a lighter transition shade. Good quality brushes to create a perfect blended lid, with a darker crease and outer v, lining the bottom waterline with eye liner and gently blending that liner into the lower lash line :) Blend well! Don't be afraid to use your (clean) fingers!  I don't believe in rigid rules when it comes to makeup - if brushes aren't doing the trick, use an index finger to blend and smudge. A decent blending brush :) Awesome fluffy brushes and nice liquid eyeliner :) Eye shadow primer! And blending brushes a must Apply eyeliner before the shadow, and reapply it afterward. It is more defined, and you have a perfect "stencil" to go over. Good products, make sure all brushes are clean and pencils etc sharpened Add a pop of navy for the perfect smoky eye! Eyeliner, mascara & the perfect blend from a smokey palette! Even false eye lashes for that wow factor! X good brushes and quality make up. a good base colour and make sure you blend correctly After all the smokiness and dark colours, pop a light highlight colour in the inner corner to brighten my eyes up a bit so it's not all dull and makes them appear bigger than they look. Good make up brushes. Start with light shadows, blend well, gradually building to a darker well blended finish. Use the lightest shadows at inner corner to darkest in outer corner method. Works every time for any smokey eye look! use a good base and lots of blending! Eye shadow primer and blending! :) I always have makeup wipes on hand to wipe off any mistakes or get rid of fall out. Even though this will remove my base makeup in the area, I can normally apply concealer/powder in the area afterwards and it gives a fresh finish. Use gel liner for your base in the the outer corner and then apply your eyeshadow powder I don't always do it the same way lol.. The best look is achieved if you use an eye primer first and then apply light base colour.  I work form the inner corners to the outer and then liquid liner.  I always end up layering on a few more times afterward until I get the right look.  Sometimes I get my silver shimmer eye shadow and using my finger tip apply that to the inner corners of my eyes Good brushes, and lots of dark brown and black shadow blended in instead of linew, then a really subtle flick :) Eyelid Primer and blending the shadows together. Starting with a base colour first to set the foundation for all the rest.practice makes prefect <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008A> Blend blend blend :*  blend well Good brushes and eye shadow primer! Use a transition colour around the outside of the dark to warm the look up and of course transition the smokiness (something creme brulee or peach smoothie from makeup geek is ideal)... and of course blend blend blend!! blend and shade!!!! awesome brushes Always start with a light hand :) you can build up! Also do you're eye makeup before foundation! Fall out gets everywhere with smokey eyes. add a liquid eyeliner wing once you're done! Sigmas E40 blending brush is a must! liquid eyeliner once you're done! get someone who knows what to do to do it for you :P Use a good blending brush and lots of eyeliner =) Use a good primer so your smokey eyes stays on all night. Use a shimmery dark brown on the lid and brush a black/blue creating a V shape around the outer corner. Keep blending until you get a soft airbrushed look :) The right brushes! Blend blend blend You can never do too much blending! Less is more.. :) make sure to always blend!!  Have a good primer and start small and build your way up!!! A good blending brush aswell as a smudging "tool" also practice! Liquid liner, black/glittery eye shadow and a really good brush to blend to get that sexy smokey affect ;) The best smokey eye is a result of good pigmented product, good brushes and most important is blending! Choosing colours that suit both your outfit and your eye colour can help tremendously too My best tip for creating the perfect smokey eye is always use tape from the bottom of your lash line and up, so the eyeshadow doesn't go where its not supposed to and it gives a nice defined look as well also make sure you always blend well! my trick is all about the right brushes, blending and smokey eyeliner Good quality make up, lots of practice and plenty of blending :-) Blending black! Build and blend!!! Smudge a little its always good to blend Make it all blend well :) xx Blend it do it all first and then through the middle put a grey from the corner of your eye to half way of your eyelid. It will look more dramatic and better. Jjust start with the light shades then, medium shades, then build the dark matte shades to gradually build your smokey eyes. From going light to dark, reduces the chances of messing up or accidentally adding to much dark eyeshadow. I'd recommend a matte dark shade, just so the shadows get enhanced when taking photographs, it's won't/shouldn't  reflect cuz it shouldn't be shimmery. So use the light/shimmery/sparkly shades last as a top off finishing coat on the middle/center of the eye lids & a matte/slightly shimmery - (can always use your pinky finger to glide off any excess glitter) highlighting the brow-bone and near the tear ducts to catch the light! AND ALWAYS BLEND, BLEND with a really soft fluffy eyeshadow brush! make sure the top & bottom of the eyes are evenly balanced with eyeshadow! line the top & bottom of the eyes for extra definition, liquid liner is recommended for the top lash line just so the eyeliner lined before doesn't smudge off because liquid liners are smudge-proof! And finishing of with a few coats of waterproof mascara to hold the eyelashes curled. Use new brushes and blend. Light inner corner to dark outer corner.  Use liquid eyeliner and mascara. Blend it thoroughly so the  lines don't look harsh x A good primer & keep blending First apply the liner creating a flick towards the end of the eyebrow, then apply your shadow blending very carefully and so you can get it even to the line, also apply shadow on undereye line too. Apply as much Mascara as you wish after curling lashes 3 times. Then repeat the eyeliner all around the eye including flick. Re apply shadow to add depth, then I like to go over the lids and flick with a black sparkling liner. Perfect!!! Buy good brushes! cant do a proper smokey eye with a bad brush :-) good blending brushes! and a light inner corner, to keep your eyes open and apart, you dont wanna look like youve got squinty eyes. end in cat eye eyeliner and flared lashes, tada! Light colour first then darker colour working from outside to middle.. Never go past the pupil! Then blend blend blend!! U can never blend to much! Then eyeliner and mascara if u have sensitive skin, always moisturise first!!  Stops u itching ur eyes and then smearing your nice eyes =) Light eyeshadow on the inner eyelid and dark on the outer and blend well. Finish with black mascara and blunt eye liner pencil. Blend blend blend! Use a brush designed to blend and use a good primer Create a smokey eye using vibrant shades that bring out the colour of your eyes. For example shades of purple for hazel and green eyes. This gives a modern take on the classic look and is stunning. :-) Quick and easy smoky eyes using Australis cosmetics! Apply cream concealer to eyelids first. This a good base so that the eye shadow doesn't rub off during the night! Next line your top and lower lashes with eye liner and use an eye liner brush to smudge the liner. Then apply brown eye shadow and sweep the colour across your eyelid, blending into the crease, continue to blend the eye shadow upward and outward on eyelids. Now use ivory eye shadow and brush it over your brow bone. To finish off your smoky eyes, apply two coats of mascara to eye lashes. Now you are ready for a night out! :) Light colour 1st then darker shade , good blending light shade inner & dark shade outer with good bursh & apply primer 1st :) :) Less is more! Always begin with a little bit of eye shadow and gradually build it up. Remember, more can be added later, but it's much more difficult to remove a particular amount of eye shadow, once it's been applied. Less is more! Always begin with a little bit of eye shadow and gradually build it up. Remember, more can be added later, but it's much more difficult to remove a particular amount of eye shadow, once it's been applied. Blending is key. Blending provides the "smokey" effect, and plus, it looks unprofessional if eye shadow has just been 'packed on'. Always clean up under the eye after you've finished your smokey eye, with concealer or foundation that has been left over on your brush. Eye shadow usually have some fall out, which can make you look like you have bags under your eyes. Hence, to polish the entire look, clean up under the eyes with concealer or foundation to really make your eyes stand out! :) Utilising a primer before applying any eye shadow at all, will definitely ensure that your smokey eye lasts all night long :) To blend out a smokey eye, never use a colour that is darker or as dark as the eye shadow applied on the lid. Always utilise a colour that will provide a smooth transition from the dark eye shadow to your crease, and then your brow bone. For example, when doing a black smokey eye, a neutral shade of brown will seamlessly blend out the black eye shadow. For a soft smokey eye, bronzed browns and golds are the best! & so glamorous! :) xx

comments:
Concentration and a steady hand are a must ! And blending with the thumb from inner edge to outer eye :D x Use a pencil liner first and then use a dip liner and finish off with a liquid liner. You need to have lighter shades of nude colours in the center of the eye lid and darker black colours on the outer eyelids. Make sure the blend of transformation is even. Finish off with a mascara and curl your eyelashes Blending the different shades thoroughly Tight lining before eyeshadow creates a good base and then blend blend blend! Instensify the colour slowly! You can always add more colour to the look, its harder to take it away! :D use a spoon! Smudge it gently and nicely. c: use cellotape to get a perfect straight wing! I don't even know how to smokey eye! Every time I try I look like a panda haha<ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B0><U+00BC> blending all the colours together well with a good eyeshadow brush to create a gradual glamorous look :) Blend and use suitable shades! Blend blend blend Having a decent brush! Lots of great smokey colours and lots of blending :) Good quality brushes to create a perfect blended lid, with a darker crease and outer v, lining the bottom waterline with eye liner and gently blending that liner into the lower lash line Blending! Also add a light colour on inner tear duct to make eyes appear bit bigger especially with all the dark around the eyes. Fake eyelashes for finishing touch! :) A good variety of brushes. Find ones that you're comfortable with and enjoy using, keep calm and remember that nothing you do is permanent - if you've made a mistake, just follow the best advice I was ever given - Blend, blend, blend!! <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008A> Using different shades of grey (hehe) Using a big fluffy brush to blend the eyeshadow out! :) Blending and smudging the eyeshadows as it helps makes a smokey eye look smokey Blend, blend and blend! :-) <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0084> Blend blend blend!! Using your finger against the side of your lid to use as a stencil for a winged smokey eye It's all about having the right brushes I reckon! You need the right blending brush and eyeshadow brush to help with application <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008A> As others have said - blend the hell out of it! Blend, blend, blend.. and remember to smoke out your lower lash line with shadows too! Experiment with a variety of colours to suit your skin tone and eye colour! I love to create a dark smokey eye with bronze, golds and dark shades of brown along with classic black :) Also lots of mascara/false lashes is essential to complete the look xx Tilleigh <U+1EE4>ltra Start lighter & gradually add the darker colour. Blend, blend blend Lots of blending! I love to use the australis grey eyeliner near the inner lashes, australis black along the lashes and smudge with my finger!!! Add a touch of navy to a smoky eye and it has that extra depth from black and silver Blend blend an more blending. Blend!! I hate seeing ment to be 'smokey eyes' and its pretty much block colours not blended :/  Blend the eyeshadow! always blend out your eyehadow! big eyelashes!!! blend! using really really full falsies! An ecotools smudge brush and a layer of concealer under your shadow for staying power Using tape to create a really crisp edge on your outer corners ;) Layer layer layer, also a smokey eye can be made with many colours Lots and lots of blending and thick lashes!! omg thx bae Tesh Kells Blend like theres no tomorrow, primer works wonders for smooth application and coat your lashes with the biggest boldest lash defying mascara out!! Blending is a must and balancing out the look by putting eyeshadow in the outer corner of the eye really finishes off the look! So often I see people with a smokey eye but they haven't balanced it out and it definitely doesn't look as nice and even. Blend blend blend!! Use good quality brushes and have lots of time. :) For impact I start my smokey shade on the eye crease which outlines the eye for that dramatic look, and blend blend blend :) Put tape on an angle just under my eye up to my eyebrow to create a nice line and area where my shadow will be. Blend, blend, blend! Have a smooth base so your eye shadow wont crease. Use tape or shadow shields on the outer V sort of area so it doesn't get messy. You can use a black eyeliner & line the lash line & the outer V & smugde with finger or blend with a blending brush, also line the water line use a black eye shadow & pat it over the base colour, use a lighter colour next to the black & use a white in the inner corner of your eye to open up the eye & also on the brow bone. Take the shadow sheilds off & blend the heck out of it haha! . Full coverage foundation always helps too & a really goods mascara aswell :) Prime your eyes! & Never forget to blend xx Definatly blending!!! Xxx Always, always prime that way it's actually going to last and doesn't become smudged over the hours which will otherwise make you look like you kissed a panda!! :) You will definitely notice a difference over the hours if you do not prime. Prime first then blend evenly & gently ... Prime your lids, use a really good blending brush and for a nice crisp line use tape at the corner of your eyes that will also help you to create the perfect wing priming and blending and patience use a primer and a dark creamy base. take extra time to make sure your blending is flawless! use tape on the outer part of your eye to make sure the shadow doesnt end up everywhere. also do your eye makeup first so you can clean up the fallout. dark colors are horrible to clean up once your foundation is already done! Keep a nice bright white or silver on the inner eye to open the eye up, blend the colours together!! 
But more importantly, practise the liquid eyeliner to perfection on the top eyelid ;) Always prime :) i use a primer first the use a light amount of eyeshadow and then Blend the colours well and I like to top it off with long and thick eyelashes and eyeliner prime first, blend colours, be patient and use white on the inner eye to open the eyes up, practice makes perfect,love to win :) Primer and blend a lot! Just blend like crazy! and then when youre done BLEND SOME MORE (: Blend blend blend! Transition colour in the crease to avoid harsh lines! Blend well!! Use Australis intensifeye for the perfect smoky eye, blending from the crease and creating a bold and intense look. Apply dark shadow with the end of a small padded eye shadow applicator, instead of using eye liner. Smokey hot!!  <3

Use cellotape to get a sharp line from the edge of the eye to the eyebrow (even works with eyeliner) Blending and practice and of course Australis cosmetics :) Gel eyeliner, 4 smokey colours, apply with a wet brush, and blend them with a eyeshadow fluffy brush. The water on the brush helps the colour stay vivid for longer! And finish with mascara of course! My biggest tip is blend blend BLEND! And practice to find out what shape and darkness suit you! :) BLEND My tips are GOOD brushes, take your time! And blend, blend, blend! making sure to blend and use a good eyeliner :) Pick one colour and its shades that make your eyes pop,layer from light to dark and blend well. Practice an blend! Make sure that the shadow starts from the crease in the eye, and that the lighter colours are on the inside of the eye, slowly blending out to grey and the black such fun playing with eyes if you want to be different, start with the darkest colour on the inner corner and gradually go lighter on the outer. also choose a colour that will make your eyes pop (purple-green eyes,blue-brown eyes, grey-blue eyes) best tip is blending it out heaps and starting out with not too much product! Black is good but sometimes I like to change it up a bit with different colours and make sure to blend properly Blend, blend, blend...and then blend some more! Practice! Be gradual and blend! put eyeliner on the top eyelid as well as the bottom Blend and extend :) Practice and use light to dark colours build it up don't got straight in with black because its harder to remove:( yes please for the kit
Thanks australias!!:) lots of blending! Blend blend blend! & it always pays to use a light hand AND to add a little product at a time. That way if you need more you can add more (better than adding a whole heap all at once) :P Layer and build your colours dont just go in with a block colour Seek advice on colours from the Australis beauty consultant, practise, then use with care and sparingly until the smokey eye effect is perfected. Blend well so you get that classic smokey eye look :) Practice Practice makes perfect, I'm still learning all the time but I'm getting better.  I find dark colours and a really good eye liner and blend.

message:
It's your last last chance to enter to win our Ultimate Eyes Pack! 
To win all you have to do is tell us, what do you do to keep your brow game on point every day?
comments:
Line, fill, set and highlight the brow bone <3 Brush them everyday as they curly and unruly!! Chuck a spoolie through it and some brow gel and out the door! Nothing. Oh wait I use an eyebrow brush or comb. Other than that not much.. I use a clear mascara to keep them in place Eyeshadow with an angled brush :) Get them tinted! I use tinted brow gel and conceal underneath. Then a little brush through. ^-^ i use australis tint my brow to tame my unruly hairs i use a gel and mascara wand through it ... and eyeshadow . mascara :) and eyelinerrrrrrrrr Fill and brush. Mine have zero colour Draw them on <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+008C><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+00B9> Pluck them! Treat, fill and set <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B2><U+0081> Clear mascara! You don't need fancy pants eyebrow gel but this pack will be perfect to fill in any spots that have been over-tweezed and make my eyebrows look perfect. Define eyebrows by filling them in a bit then highlight brow bone :) Firstly use a brow pencil, make sure to comb it through so they're well shaped, and then set them with a slightly darker powder so no hairs pop out of place during the day, and my colour is more perfectly matched! xx Brow brush and a perfectly matched eyeshadow :) I use eyebrow cake powder. Very natural Brow gel to stop those strays from ruining my form! Fill them in!  can hardly see my natural ones so it makes a big difference haha! <3 My $2 shop pencil works wonders!! I use two mirrors to make sure no strays have popped up!, a bit of brown shadow - brown pencil and Im good to go! Unfortunately it involves colouring them in & trying to make them appear fuller. Too much over plucking has lead to them to stop growing. message:
Hashtag spring nails!! So simple. So lush. So angular.
1. Apply a base coat of your favourite spring pastel. Weï¿½ve gone for the dreamy Friend Like Me.
2. Once completely dry, cover half of each nail by placing a small piece of tape across diagonally. We find Scotch tape works best, as the others can leave sticky residue.
3. Apply a complementary spring colour on top. Weï¿½ve chosen Citrus.
4. Only when itï¿½s completely dry should you remove the tape. Voila! Donï¿½t forget your top coat!

1. Apply a good coat of your favourite vibrant shade. Weï¿½ve gone for AC/ME Red Hot Chilli Pepper.
2. Once theyï¿½ve completely dried, cut thin triangles out of sticky tape and place in the centre of each nail. Allow the base of the triangle to hang over your cuticle.

4. Once dry, carefully peel off the tape from each finger and presto. Apply your topcoat, sit back and bask in your glory.

1. Pull back the eyelid and completely dry your waterline with a cotton tip. Your eyeliner wonï¿½t stick if itï¿½s still wet.
2. Apply a good coat of eyeliner to your waterline. Weï¿½ve chosen our Black Liner.
3. Do the same for your upper waterline.
4. Clean up any oopsies with a cotton tip.

message: Ever broken a powder compact? Never fear - with a little rubbing alcohol you can repair it like new! Simply mix the alcohol with the powder, a little at a time, and when the consistency is that of a paste, mix and flatten with a spoon. Leave a tissue on top and wait for it to set! #ACSolutions

Get yourself some serious FIERCE eyes with our 'The Eyes Have It' competition! WIN this pack of goodies featuring 5 of the Cray For Colour eye pencils, the Browz It kit as well as our brand new Fierce Eyes mascara! Tell us how you style your signature eye make up look to enter. T&Cï¿½s apply.
comments: First a soft shade to act as a brightening base, then a metallic soft gold or taupe on the lid with a touch of smokey black through the crease Rose gold and warm browns with a soft gold in the water line, long lashes and wings Bottom left of the photo says 'open to NZ residents 13+ only, ends 29/03/2015'? Can you please rectify the date? Thanks I have like a ombre style eye that goes from white to brown from the inner corner to out then I have eyeliner with flicks and then masacra brows lightly penciled in with brown, comb through with spoolie to soften; eyesshadow primer as base (or champagne/light-colour cream shadow),  champagne or soft shimmer on lid, darker shade blend through the crease and outer-V, plum or brown liner smudged slightly, curling brown mascara :) I love my australis oh Hai brow I shape my eyebrows and then put the powder under the brow bone to highlight and then I always have a gold ombre to black eyeshadow and a bold colour or black wing with full mascara or lashes <U+263A><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+008A><ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+0080> I like to start with a light tone alone my brow bone then a dark charcoal in the crease of my eye lid and deep silver on the main part of my eyelid. i then like to put a dash of a lighter colour in the corners of my eyes to make them appear more opened up and i finish off with a black kohl eyeliner (smudged of course) and tonnes of mascara <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B8><U+0084> I'm a bit old-fashioned, a layer of primer, brown shimmer, and a bit of glitter on top to make the eyes pop, I then put a darker brown around the top of the eyelid..I wear glasses so no one probably notices anyway! My signiture eye look consists of earthy brown tones and oranges. I like doing a smokey eye and using a black eyeliner to emphasize my inner corner. Orange and brown tones make my blue eyes pop and the black eyeliner makes the look so much better. I'm pretty boring with brown tones usually, and every so often add a really bright pop of colour into the inner corner! I love using the screw up coloured Australis eyeliner! My signature eye look begins with a primer over my lids. After that, I apply a shade that is slightly lighter than my skin tone under the eyebrow on the brow bone and blend that down, adding a slightly darker shade over my entire lid. Then I apply a light gold shimmery shadow below the crease, and then use a medium brown in the crease and blend that in. If I'm going for something a little bit flashier, I'll sometimes apply a pink shimmer toward the inner corner of the eye, and the same brown used in the crease in the outer corner. Occasionally I'll run a little bit of the gold shadow under my waterline on the lower of my eye. Follow that up with a subtle brown eyeliner, and then finish off with a dark brown mascara. For my brows I usually just use an angled brush to apply some brown eyeshadow, and set it with a brow setting gel. I'm trying to go out of my comfort zone and get into some stronger and more interesting colours, as this look is usually fairly subtle. Cheers for the opportunity to participate in the competition :) I don't wear eye make up currently but would start with this great set, will read the comments for great tips. Bronzed up eyes, defined brows and a pop of colour on the lower lash line <ed><U+00A0><U+00BD><ed><U+00B1><U+008C><ed><U+00A0><U+00BC><ed><U+00BF><U+00BD><U+2600><U+FE0F> A light brush of Australis Cosmetics Bronzing Powder, a smidge of Australis Cosmetics Gold Gaga Metallix Eyeshadow, a fine smudged line of Australis Cosmetics Cray for Colour 'Drawn to Diamonds' Eye Pencil & finish it all off with a coat of Australis Cosmetics Fierce Eyes Mascara wink emoticon

I love to K.I.S.S my eye make up- Keep It Simple Silly with smoky brown  highlights to bring out my blue eyes. It's a simple look but it's beautiful especially when matches with effortlessly toussled hair! I follow my 3 E's.

Step one: Enhance. I have brown eyes so I like to enhance them with purple mascara and a smudge of purple eye shadow along the top and bottom lash line to bring out the brown. 

Step two: Elevate. Two wings - one so sharp and fierce it could kill a man and the other so wobbly you'd think a child with a crayon did it in comparison to Van Gogh's art on the left eye. But in the end, they're wings and they help me soar through my day :)  

Step three: Errrhm eyebrows. I'll fill 'em in based on my mood and what I want the world to see me as that day.

And I'm set! I like a simple, classic look so just some liquid black eyeliner along my upper and lower lash line, with a gentle upward sweep at the corner, and some quality volumizing and lengthening black mascara to finish it off. I start off with my eyeliner, wing it and then go on to the mascara to achieve nice and long eyelashes, and if I am bothered, I would also fill in my brows Love wearing my false lashes, and enhancing them with only the most FIERCE mascara! Taupes and golds are my go-to shades, as they brighten my eyes and make them look larger! Paired with inky winged black liquid liner, voluminous mascara coated lashes(..maybe even falsies ;)) and perfectly on point brows, this look can take me from day to night in a flash! I like to do a smokey eye using metallic kinda colours and i finish the look with a simple winged liner and do half of my bottom lid with black or white eyeliner depending on my mood A Shimmer of shadow.. A lick of Mascara and a winged eye, which takes precision but then makes my eyes POP! :) Just a question Australis Cosmetics the end dates says 29/03/2015? I presume this isnt correct.
